20. Test each Product Controller endpoint
Generate traffic for the list endpoint:
for i in {1..100}; do
  curl --cacert "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" \
    -s -o /dev/null \
    https://localhost:8181/api/products
done
Generate traffic for a product ID:
for i in {1..100}; do
  curl --cacert "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" \
    -s -o /dev/null \
    https://localhost:8181/api/products/1
done
Generate traffic for active products:
for i in {1..100}; do
  curl --cacert "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" \
    -s -o /dev/null \
    https://localhost:8181/api/products/active
done
After generating traffic, change the dashboard variables:
GET → /api/products
GET → /api/products/{id}
GET → /api/products/active
The same panels should update without creating endpoint-specific copies.
Important considerations
•
Use $__rate_interval instead of hardcoding [1m]; Grafana adjusts it to the dashboard range and Prometheus scrape interval.
•
Use =~"$method" and =~"$uri" because the variables support multiple selections and All.
•
Do not add query parameters such as keyword, page or category as metric tags.
•
Do not create product-ID labels.
•
Avoid choosing All endpoints when comparing endpoint latency; combining very different operations can hide a slow route.
•
Use the endpoint variable for HTTP panels, but leave CPU, heap and database panels service-wide.
•
Keep p95 as the main service-level latency indicator; use p99 to expose tail latency and p50 to show typical behavior.